3F-ubfWdWMp-jMmTnsJWlip-LHdD1_isfPFJ51BoSs0rjSTSd52w4y4csc-5q4x2o0g6BVBQvUo=
PfU_xlfnDyc-7oMGdfKrifBnpEWHw ) : my objection to Title II was not because =
I was opposed to net neutrality, but rather that I recognized the tremendou=
s costs and ultimate limitations in availability and velocity that accompan=
y bureaucratic processes ill-suited to the task at hand (in this case rules=
 designed to limit China that end up applied to every single AI use case ar=
ound the world).

Secondly, and along those lines, this introduces a fundamentally new paradi=
gm to U.S. tech regulation. Until now the U.S. has operated with a presumpt=
ion of openness, with targeted controls on various technologies (which have=
 changed and evolved over time). Yes, this allows stuff to slip through the=
 cracks, but defaulting to openness means defaulting to innovation and worl=
dwide expansion, which undergirds the U.S. tech industry=E2=80=99s worldwid=
e dominance. To put it in legal terms, tech has operated in an =E2=80=9Cinn=
ocent until proven guilty=E2=80=9D paradigm.

These regulations, however, change that around: now GPU purchasers are guil=
ty until proven innocent. Exports, and all of the innovation and expansion =
that follows, need permission by default. This will not only slow things do=
wn, but critically, it also sets the stage for similar intrusions into tech=
 markets in the future.

Back in 2021 I wrote an Article called Apple=E2=80=99s Mistake ( https://st=
ratechery.com/2021/apples-mistake/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZ=
CI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJ=
hdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIi=
