COVq_J2aOg ) about the company=E2=80=99s misguided attempt to scan for CSAM=
 on your phone (a policy that the company later backed down from):

The fundamental issue =E2=80=94 and the first reason why I think Apple made=
 a mistake here =E2=80=94 is that there is a meaningful difference between =
capability and policy. One of the most powerful arguments in Apple=E2=80=99=
s favor in the 2016 San Bernardino case is that the company didn=E2=80=99t =
even have the means to break into the iPhone in question, and that to build=
 the capability would open the company up to a multitude of requests that w=
ere far less pressing in nature, and weaken the company=E2=80=99s ability t=
o stand up to foreign governments. In this case, though, Apple is building =
the capability, and the only thing holding the company back is policy.

This paragraph isn=E2=80=99t perfectly applicable to this case =E2=80=94 th=
e Biden administration believes the U.S. government has the capability to e=
stablish a permission structure for tech exports =E2=80=94 but the overall =
idea about the danger of crossing a line is pertinent: you might be able to=
 make a case that these rules are necessary for AI and won=E2=80=99t be tha=
t damaging to U.S. industry in the short to medium-term, but I do worry abo=
ut crossing the line to a world where the government feels comfortable esta=
blishing an E.U.-like assumption that you have to ask permission to do some=
thing, instead of focusing regulations on telling what you can not.

